  "description": "Ilinx is one of Roger Caillois\u0026rsquo;s four fundamental categories of play: play structured around vertigo — the temporary disruption of stable perception. Spinning, swinging, roller coasters, extreme sports, whirling dervish rituals, and certain ecstatic practices all produce ilinx. The player seeks not mastery (agon), not fate (alea), not transformation (mimicry), but disorientation itself — the thrill of losing control in a controlled context. The appeal is the momentary destruction of ordinary bodily stability, followed by its recovery.\n",
